<section id="overview">
  <h2>Living in Rome</h2>
  <p class="lede">Rome is one of the oldest and most influential cities in the world, with a history that spans over 2,500 years. It is the capital of Italy and the seat of the Roman Catholic Church, as well as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Living in Rome as an expat can be both rewarding and challenging.</p>
  <p>You can enjoy the beauty and culture of the city, but also face the difficulties of traffic, bureaucracy, and pollution. Rome is a city of contrasts, where ancient monuments coexist with modern buildings, and where tradition and innovation blend together.</p>
  <p>Rome is the most populous city in Italy, with about 2.8 million inhabitants. It is also the core of the wider Rome metropolitan area, which is estimated to have between 4.2 million and 6.7 million people. Rome is the political and administrative capital of Italy and a major cultural and tourist center.</p>
  <p>It is known for its landmarks, such as the Colosseum, the Pantheon, the Vatican, and the Trevi Fountain. It has a GDP of about €200 billion ($246 billion), making it the fourth richest city in Italy and one of the largest economies in Europe.</p>

