<section id="generalinfo">
  <h2>What is Rome like?</h2>
  <p>Rome is a historical and artistic city, with a rich and diverse population. It is home to people from different countries, religions and backgrounds, who contribute to the city's social and cultural life. Rome is also a cultural and artistic center, with a long and glorious history and heritage. It hosts many museums, galleries, theaters, festivals and events, covering various fields of interest, such as art, music, literature, cinema, religion and sports. Some of the most famous cultural attractions in Rome are the Vatican Museums, the Sistine Chapel, the Roman Forum, the Capitoline Museums, the Borghese Gallery and the National Museum of Rome.</p>

  <h3>Climate</h3>
  <p>Rome has a Mediterranean climate, with mild winters and warm to hot summers. It is located in central Italy, on a plain, and about 25 km (15 mi) from the Tyrrhenian Sea. The average temperature of the coldest month (January) is 7.7&nbsp;°C (46&nbsp;°F), that of the warmest months (July, August) is 25.6&nbsp;°C (78&nbsp;°F). Precipitation amounts to about 800 mm (31.5 in) per year; the wettest season is autumn, followed by winter.</p>
  <p>In summer, it's hot and sunny &mdash; great for nightlife, but afternoon thunderstorms and high humidity are common. Winters are mild and quite rainy, occasionally cold at night, with rare and light snowfalls. Spring and autumn are pleasant and variable, with both rain and sun.</p>

  <h3>Economy</h3>
  <p>Rome is the political and administrative capital of Italy, and a major cultural and tourist center. It has a mixed and diversified economy, based on public administration, services, tourism, commerce, media, entertainment, education, and research. It is also a hub for innovation and creativity, hosting several universities, academies and institutes, such as the Sapienza University of Rome, LUISS, the Rome University of Fine Arts, and the National Research Council.</p>
  <p>Rome offers many opportunities for highly skilled professionals, but it is also a very expensive and congested city, where quality of life is often affected by traffic, pollution, bureaucracy, and corruption. About 14% of the population lives below the poverty line, and about 11% is unemployed.</p>

  <h3>Education</h3>
  <p>Rome has several public and private universities and colleges, offering a wide range of courses and degrees. Some of the most prestigious are the Sapienza University of Rome, LUISS, the Pontifical Gregorian University, and the John Cabot University. The city also has many international schools, including the American Overseas School of Rome, St.&nbsp;George's British International School, the Marymount International School, and the Rome International School.</p>

