<section id="costofliving">
  <h2>Cost of living in Rome</h2>
  <p>The cost of living in Rome is high compared to most other Italian cities, but still lower than <a href="https://expiter.com/blog/living-in-milan/">Milan</a> and <a href="https://expiter.com/blog/living-in-venice/">Venice</a>. A family of four's estimated monthly costs are around €4,000 without rent; a single person's are around €2,400 without rent.</p>
  <p>Rent is also high, especially in the city centre. A one-bedroom apartment in the centre costs about €800 per month, while a three-bedroom apartment costs about €1,600 per month. Food, transportation, utilities and entertainment are also higher than the national average.</p>
</section>

<section id="povertyandsafety">
  <h2>Is Rome safe?</h2>
  <p>Rome is a relatively safe city to visit, with a moderate crime rate compared to other major cities in Italy and Europe. The most common crimes are pickpocketing, bag-snatching, scams and vandalism, which usually target crowded and touristy places &mdash; the city center, railway stations, the metro and buses. Stay vigilant, keep valuables close, avoid suspicious or aggressive people, and report any incident to the police.</p>
  <p>Rome is generally safe at night, but avoid walking alone in dark and isolated streets. Some areas to avoid include Tor Bella Monaca, Romanina, San Basilio and Corviale, which are affected by drug trafficking, theft, and delinquency.</p>
</section>

