  <h3>Advantages of living in Rome</h3>
  <p>Rome is a historical and artistic city with a rich and diverse culture. You can explore its many attractions &mdash; ancient monuments, museums, art galleries, churches and fountains &mdash; and immerse yourself in its history. It is also a religious capital, with the Vatican City and the Pope based in the city. The public transport system makes it easy to reach other major Italian cities such as <a href="https://expiter.com/blog/living-in-florence/">Florence</a>, <a href="https://expiter.com/blog/living-in-naples/">Naples</a> and <a href="https://expiter.com/blog/living-in-venice/">Venice</a>. The food and wine are famous for their quality and regional variety.</p>

  <h3>Disadvantages of living in Rome</h3>
  <p>Rome can be expensive and challenging. Affordable housing is hard to find, especially in the city centre. The city can be crowded and noisy &mdash; particularly during peak tourist season &mdash; and polluted, with poor air quality and traffic congestion. The language barrier can be a challenge if you don't speak Italian, and the bureaucratic lifestyle can be frustrating. Summers can be scorching and humid.</p>
</section>

<section id="faqs">
  <h2>FAQs</h2>

  <h3>What is Rome like for foreigners?</h3>
  <p>Rome attracts many expats from different countries and backgrounds. Living here as an expat is both rewarding and challenging: you enjoy the culture, history, art and cuisine, but also deal with the high cost of living, the language barrier, bureaucracy and pollution. Best areas for expats include Trastevere, Monti, Testaccio and Prati.</p>

  <h3>What is Rome like for students?</h3>
  <p>Rome offers a wide range of academic programs, from arts and humanities to engineering and sciences, across public, private and international institutions. Students benefit from a stimulating learning environment, a diverse student community, a rich cultural offer and good internship opportunities &mdash; though high cost of living, limited accommodation and complex bureaucracy are real constraints.</p>

  <h3>Is Rome a fun city?</h3>
  <p>Rome combines ancient and modern, with monuments, ruins, churches and museums alongside lively nightlife. Areas like Trastevere, Testaccio, Monti, Pigneto and San Lorenzo are great for going out. Live music, comedy and theater run at venues like Auditorium Parco della Musica, Teatro dell'Opera, Teatro Sistina and Teatro Vittoria.</p>

  <h3>Is Rome walkable?</h3>
  <p>Rome has low walkability &mdash; it is huge, chaotic, and crowded with tourists and traffic. Public transport suffers frequent delays and strikes. That said, the city offers a rich historical and artistic heritage, a vibrant atmosphere, and a mild sunny climate for most of the year, which makes pedestrian exploration rewarding in spite of the friction.</p>
</section>

